{"title_page": "Neum\u00fcnster", "text_new": "{{Infobox German location\n|type                   = Town\n|image_coa                = Wappen neumuenster.svg\n|image_photo           = City hall Neumuenster Germany.jpg\n|image_caption = City hall\n|coordinates           = {{coord|54|04|17|N|09|59|24|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|state            = Schleswig-Holstein\n|district                 = urban\n|elevation                  = 22\n|area                = 71.57\n|population             = 78137\n|Stand                 = 2006-06-30\n|postal_code                   = 24534 - 24539\n|area_code               = 04321\n|licence                   = NMS\n|Gemeindeschl\u00fcssel     = 01 0 04 000\n|divisions            = 9 [[Stadtbezirk]]e\n|website               = {{official|https://www.neumuenster.de/}}\n|mayor         = Dr. Olaf Tauras \n|B\u00fcrgermeistertitel    = Oberb\u00fcrgermeister\n|party                = CDU\n}}\n[[File:Neum\u00fcnster Vicelinkirche 1.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Vicelinkirche (''Vicelin Church'')]]\n\n'''Neum\u00fcnster''' ({{IPA-de|n\u0254\u028f\u02c8m\u028fnst\u0250}}) is an [[Independent cities of Germany|urban municipality]] in the middle of [[Schleswig-Holstein]], [[Germany]]. With more than 79,000 registered inhabitants, it is the fourth-largest municipality in [[Schleswig-Holstein]] (behind [[Kiel]], [[L\u00fcbeck]] and [[Flensburg]]).\n\n==History==\nThe first historic record of the precursor village \"Wippendorf\" dates from 1127.\n\n==Current situation==\n[[Neum\u00fcnster station]] is a major railway junction with lines running in six (formerly seven) directions, including the important [[Hamburg-Altona\u2013Kiel railway|Hamburg-Altona\u2013Kiel]] and [[Neum\u00fcnster\u2013Flensburg railway|Neum\u00fcnster\u2013Flensburg lines]].\n\nNear Neum\u00fcnster at [[Ehndorf]], there is a high-power [[medium wave]] transmission facility for transmitting the program of [[Deutschlandfunk]], the [[Ehndorf transmitter]], which is often named incorrectly as \"Neum\u00fcnster transmitter\".\n\n==Geography==\nNeum\u00fcnster is located at river [[Schwale]], near the geographical center of Schleswig-Holstein, {{convert|35|km|mi}} south of [[Kiel]], {{convert|65|km|mi}} north of [[Hamburg]] and {{convert|72|km|mi}} west of [[L\u00fcbeck]]. The [[Aukrug Nature Park]] is close to the town.\n\n==Mayors and Lord mayors==\nIn 1870 Neum\u00fcnster received the town privileges. Since 1904 Max R\u00f6er was the Lord mayor.<ref>[http://www.neumuenster.de/cms/index.php?article_id=59 B\u00fcrgermeister] auf neum\u00fcnster.de</ref>\n* 1870\u20131894: Eduard Schlichting\n* 1894\u20131919: Max R\u00f6er\n* 1919\u20131933: Detlef Schmidt\n* 1933\u20131945: Max Stahmer (NSDAP)\n* 1945\u20131946: Gustav B\u00e4rwald (Oberstadtdirektor)\n* 1946\u20131948: Ludolf Behnke (CDU)\n* 1948\u20131950: Hugo Vo\u00df (SPD)\n* 1950\u20131970: Walther Lehmkuhl (SPD)\n* 1970\u20131988: Uwe Harder (SPD)\n* 1988\u20131991: Franz-Josef Pr\u00f6pper (SPD)\n* 1991\u20132009: Hartmut Unterlehberg (SPD)\n* since September 2009: Olaf Tauras (CDU)\n\n==Population development==\n*1803: 2,588\n*1900: 27,335\n*1939: 54,094\n*1946: 66,185\n*1972: 86,745\n*2005: 78,333\n*2012: 76,951\n*2015: 79,197\n\nThe 10 largest groups of foreign residents by the end of 2018 are :\n\n{|\n|-\n|{{Flag|Turkey}}||1,760\n|-\n|{{Flag|Syria}}||1,320\n|-\n|{{Flag|Poland}}||995\n|-\n|{{Flag|Bulgaria}}||970\n|-\n|{{Flag|Romania}}||875\n|-\n|{{Flag|Afghanistan}}||690\n|-\n|{{Flag|Iraq}}||515\n|-\n|{{Flag|Russia}}||295\n|-\n|{{Flag|Iran}}||250\n|-\n|{{Flag|Croatia}}||205\n|}\n\n==Notable residents==\n[[File:NMS-St.Maria-St.Vicelin-Kirche (7).JPG|thumb|150px|Memorial plate Eduard M\u00fcller in Neum\u00fcnster]]\n[[File:Staatsministerin ChristineHaderthauer.jpg|thumb|150px|Christine Haderthauer]]\n[[File:Panik - Jetix-Award - YOU 2008 Berlin (6915).jpg|thumb|150px|Panik 2008]]\n* [[Ernst Eduard Hudemann]] (1811\u20131889) educator, philologist and classical historian.\n* [[Eduard Sachau]] (1845\u20131930) [[Oriental studies|orientalist]]\n* [[Karl Schlabow]] (1891\u20131984) archaeologist, museum director and conservator \n* Helmut Johannsen (1908-?), dentist and SS Obersturmbannf\u00fchrer, chief dentist in the Buchenlager concentration camp\n* The Blessed [[Eduard M\u00fcller (martyr)|Eduard M\u00fcller]] (1911-1943), Catholic priest, one of the [[L\u00fcbeck martyrs]]\n* [[Gerhard Wessel]] (1913-2002), President of the [[Federal Intelligence Service (Germany)|Federal Intelligence Bureau]] 1968/1978\n* [[Herbert Hagen|Herbert Martin Hagen]] (1913-1999), SS Stormbolder and Head of the Jewish Council\n* [[Horst Mittelstaedt]] (1923-2016), biologist cyberneticist and university lecturer\n* [[Detlev Blanke]] (1941-2016) University lecturer for interlinguistics at the [[Humboldt-Universit\u00e4t Berlin]]\n* [[Wilf Smith (footballer born 1946)|Wilf Smith]] (born 1946) former professional footballer, made 432 pro appearances \n* [[Werner B\u00fchse]] (born 1951) former sports shooter, competed at the [[1968 Summer Olympics]] \n* [[Michael Simon (stage director)|Michael Simon]] (born 1958) theatre director, opera director and scenic designer\n* [[Thomas Mohr (tenor)]] (born 1961), tenor and academic teacher\n* [[Christine Haderthauer]] (born 1962), former CSU General Secretary and former Minister of State (Bavarian State Ministry of Labor and Social Affairs, Family and Women)\n* [[Svenja Schlicht]] (born 1967), swimmer, competed in the [[1984 Summer Olympics|1984]] and the [[1988 Summer Olympics]]\n* [[Dirk Urban]] (born 1969) retired shot putter, competed at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]] \n* [[Stefan Schnoor]], (born 1971), retired footballer, 358 pro appearances\n* [[Gabriel Silberstein]] (born 1974) former professional tennis player, emigrated to Chile.\n* [[Mona Barthel]], (born 1990), tennis player\n* [[Panik (band)|Panik]] (founded 2002) rock band, formerly named Pan!k.\n\n==See also==\n*[[VfR Neum\u00fcnster]]\n*[[Hans Fallada Prize]]\n*[[Einfelder See]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat}}\n*{{wikivoyage-inline|Neum\u00fcnster}}\n*{{in lang|de}} [http://www.neumuenster.de/ Official website]\n\n{{Germany districts schleswig-holstein}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Neumunster}}\n[[Category:Neum\u00fcnster| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Schleswig-Holstein]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox German location\n|type                   = Town\n|image_coa                = Wappen neumuenster.svg\n|image_photo           = City hall Neumuenster Germany.jpg\n|image_caption = City hall\n|coordinates           = {{coord|54|04|17|N|09|59|24|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|Karte                 = Lage der kreisfreien Stadt Neum\u00fcnster in Deutschland.png\n|state            = Schleswig-Holstein\n|district                 = urban\n|elevation                  = 22\n|area                = 71.57\n|population             = 78137\n|Stand                 = 2006-06-30\n|postal_code                   = 24534 - 24539\n|area_code               = 04321\n|licence                   = NMS\n|Gemeindeschl\u00fcssel     = 01 0 04 000\n|NUTS                  = DEFO4\n|LOCODE                = DE NEU\n|divisions            = 9 [[Stadtbezirk]]e\n|Adresse               = Gro\u00dfflecken 59<br />24534 Neum\u00fcnster\n|website               = {{official|https://www.neumuenster.de/}}\n|mayor         = Dr. Olaf Tauras \n|B\u00fcrgermeistertitel    = Oberb\u00fcrgermeister\n|party                = CDU\n}}\n[[File:Neum\u00fcnster Vicelinkirche 1.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Vicelinkirche (''Vicelin Church'')]]\n\n'''Neum\u00fcnster''' ({{IPA-de|n\u0254\u028f\u02c8m\u028fnst\u0250}}) is an [[Independent cities of Germany|urban municipality]] in the middle of [[Schleswig-Holstein]], [[Germany]]. With more than 79,000 registered inhabitants, it is the fourth-largest municipality in [[Schleswig-Holstein]] (behind [[Kiel]], [[L\u00fcbeck]] and [[Flensburg]]).\n\n==History==\nThe first historic record of the precursor village \"Wippendorf\" dates from 1127.\n\n==Current situation==\n[[Neum\u00fcnster station]] is a major railway junction with lines running in six (formerly seven) directions, including the important [[Hamburg-Altona\u2013Kiel railway|Hamburg-Altona\u2013Kiel]] and [[Neum\u00fcnster\u2013Flensburg railway|Neum\u00fcnster\u2013Flensburg lines]].\n\nNear Neum\u00fcnster at [[Ehndorf]], there is a high-power [[medium wave]] transmission facility for transmitting the program of [[Deutschlandfunk]], the [[Ehndorf transmitter]], which is often named incorrectly as \"Neum\u00fcnster transmitter\".\n\n==Geography==\nNeum\u00fcnster is located at river [[Schwale]], near the geographical center of Schleswig-Holstein, {{convert|35|km|mi}} south of [[Kiel]], {{convert|65|km|mi}} north of [[Hamburg]] and {{convert|72|km|mi}} west of [[L\u00fcbeck]]. The [[Aukrug Nature Park]] is close to the town.\n\n==Mayors and Lord mayors==\nIn 1870 Neum\u00fcnster received the town privileges. Since 1904 Max R\u00f6er was the Lord mayor.<ref>[http://www.neumuenster.de/cms/index.php?article_id=59 B\u00fcrgermeister] auf neum\u00fcnster.de</ref>\n* 1870\u20131894: Eduard Schlichting\n* 1894\u20131919: Max R\u00f6er\n* 1919\u20131933: Detlef Schmidt\n* 1933\u20131945: Max Stahmer (NSDAP)\n* 1945\u20131946: Gustav B\u00e4rwald (Oberstadtdirektor)\n* 1946\u20131948: Ludolf Behnke (CDU)\n* 1948\u20131950: Hugo Vo\u00df (SPD)\n* 1950\u20131970: Walther Lehmkuhl (SPD)\n* 1970\u20131988: Uwe Harder (SPD)\n* 1988\u20131991: Franz-Josef Pr\u00f6pper (SPD)\n* 1991\u20132009: Hartmut Unterlehberg (SPD)\n* since September 2009: Olaf Tauras (CDU)\n\n==Population development==\n*1803: 2,588\n*1900: 27,335\n*1939: 54,094\n*1946: 66,185\n*1972: 86,745\n*2005: 78,333\n*2012: 76,951\n*2015: 79,197\n\nThe 10 largest groups of foreign residents by the end of 2018 are :\n\n{|\n|-\n|{{Flag|Turkey}}||1,760\n|-\n|{{Flag|Syria}}||1,320\n|-\n|{{Flag|Poland}}||995\n|-\n|{{Flag|Bulgaria}}||970\n|-\n|{{Flag|Romania}}||875\n|-\n|{{Flag|Afghanistan}}||690\n|-\n|{{Flag|Iraq}}||515\n|-\n|{{Flag|Russia}}||295\n|-\n|{{Flag|Iran}}||250\n|-\n|{{Flag|Croatia}}||205\n|}\n\n==Notable residents==\n[[File:NMS-St.Maria-St.Vicelin-Kirche (7).JPG|thumb|150px|Memorial plate Eduard M\u00fcller in Neum\u00fcnster]]\n[[File:Staatsministerin ChristineHaderthauer.jpg|thumb|150px|Christine Haderthauer]]\n[[File:Panik - Jetix-Award - YOU 2008 Berlin (6915).jpg|thumb|150px|Panik 2008]]\n* [[Ernst Eduard Hudemann]] (1811\u20131889) educator, philologist and classical historian.\n* [[Eduard Sachau]] (1845\u20131930) [[Oriental studies|orientalist]]\n* [[Karl Schlabow]] (1891\u20131984) archaeologist, museum director and conservator \n* Helmut Johannsen (1908-?), dentist and SS Obersturmbannf\u00fchrer, chief dentist in the Buchenlager concentration camp\n* The Blessed [[Eduard M\u00fcller (martyr)|Eduard M\u00fcller]] (1911-1943), Catholic priest, one of the [[L\u00fcbeck martyrs]]\n* [[Gerhard Wessel]] (1913-2002), President of the [[Federal Intelligence Service (Germany)|Federal Intelligence Bureau]] 1968/1978\n* [[Herbert Hagen|Herbert Martin Hagen]] (1913-1999), SS Stormbolder and Head of the Jewish Council\n* [[Horst Mittelstaedt]] (1923-2016), biologist cyberneticist and university lecturer\n* [[Detlev Blanke]] (1941-2016) University lecturer for interlinguistics at the [[Humboldt-Universit\u00e4t Berlin]]\n* [[Wilf Smith (footballer born 1946)|Wilf Smith]] (born 1946) former professional footballer, made 432 pro appearances \n* [[Werner B\u00fchse]] (born 1951) former sports shooter, competed at the [[1968 Summer Olympics]] \n* [[Michael Simon (stage director)|Michael Simon]] (born 1958) theatre director, opera director and scenic designer\n* [[Thomas Mohr (tenor)]] (born 1961), tenor and academic teacher\n* [[Christine Haderthauer]] (born 1962), former CSU General Secretary and former Minister of State (Bavarian State Ministry of Labor and Social Affairs, Family and Women)\n* [[Svenja Schlicht]] (born 1967), swimmer, competed in the [[1984 Summer Olympics|1984]] and the [[1988 Summer Olympics]]\n* [[Dirk Urban]] (born 1969) retired shot putter, competed at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]] \n* [[Stefan Schnoor]], (born 1971), retired footballer, 358 pro appearances\n* [[Gabriel Silberstein]] (born 1974) former professional tennis player, emigrated to Chile.\n* [[Mona Barthel]], (born 1990), tennis player\n* [[Panik (band)|Panik]] (founded 2002) rock band, formerly named Pan!k.\n\n==See also==\n*[[VfR Neum\u00fcnster]]\n*[[Hans Fallada Prize]]\n*[[Einfelder See]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat}}\n*{{wikivoyage-inline|Neum\u00fcnster}}\n*{{in lang|de}} [http://www.neumuenster.de/ Official website]\n\n{{Germany districts schleswig-holstein}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Neumunster}}\n[[Category:Neum\u00fcnster| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Schleswig-Holstein]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neum%C3%BCnster"}
{"title_page": "Dominic Certo", "text_new": "{{short description|American businessperson and author|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Dominic Certo\n| occupation = Businessperson and writer\n| image = Dominic Certo photo.jpg\n| awards = [[American Book Award]] nomination\n| notable_works = ''The Valor of Francesco D'Amini''\n}}\n'''Dominic Certo''' is an American businessperson and author. He has been nominated for the American Book Award, and served as an international judge for the [[International Federation of BodyBuilding & Fitness]] (IFBB).\n\n==Career==\nDominic Certo served in the [[United States Marine Corps]] and is a veteran of the [[Vietnam War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.questia.com/magazine/1G1-452290683/book-review-gold-in-the-coffins|title=\"Book Review: Gold in the Coffins\" |author=Spiro, Keith |date=April 2016 |publisher=The Exceptional Parent}}</ref>  He has since served as an advisor and Chairman of the Advisory Board for [[Operation Homefront]].<ref name=Fox /> In business, Certo has served as President of Hillside Publications,<ref>{{cite book |page=660 |title=Publishers Directory |publisher=Gale Research Company |year=2003}}</ref> and Chairman of The Certo Group, a food services company<ref>{{cite book |page=693 |title=Directory of Chain Restaurant Operators |publisher=Business Guides, Incorporated |year=2008}}</ref> founded by Certo in 1985 and which went public in 2004. He also ran a restaurant chain called LA Caf\u00e9. Certo was knighted by the Royal Family of The Reigning Order of St. John in Russia. He has also received two Presidential Volunteer Service Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=24458787|title=The Certo Group Corp.: Private Company Information - Bloomberg|website=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\n==Bodybuilding==\nIn 1981 Certo was named by the IFBB a judge for that year's [[Mr. Olympia]] competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=KaZeDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT139|title=Muscle Wars|first=Rick|last=Wayne|date=1 January 1985|publisher=BookBaby|via=Google Books|page=139}}</ref> From 1980 to 1986 he served as the Director of the Professional Division Judging for the IFBB, and from 1985 to 1990 he was the Vice President of the Professional Division. He was also the co-producer and director for the 1988 Mr. Olympia and was the awarded the IFBB Silver Medal. Certo is both now a coach and a prior national competitor in the sport himself.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bizstanding.com/p/ifbb-42134058|title=IFBB - Company Profile - BizStanding|website=bizstanding.com}}</ref>\n\n==Writing==\nCerto wrote the book ''The Valor of Francesco D'Amini'', a fictionalized account of a Marine platoon during the Vietnam War.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=_GPXCwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq|title=The Valor of Francesco D'Amini|first=Dominic N.|last=Certo|date=19 April 2016|publisher=Open Road Media|via=Google Books}}</ref> It was nominated for the 1980 [[American Book Award]], and received the 1979 ''Vega'''s Writer Award for Prose.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=QIo6k_tQ0uwC&pg=PA113|title=Success-Pure and Simple: How to Make It in Business, Sports and the Arts!|first=Dominic Certo|last=KSJ|date=1 December 2006|page=113}}</ref> In 2006 Certo self-published the book ''Success-Pure and Simple: How to Make It in Business, Sports and the Arts!'', which focuses on using lessons from athletics and applying them to various professional fields.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books/about/Success_Pure_and_Simple.html?id=QIo6k_tQ0uwC&hl=en&output=html_text&redir_esc=y|title=Success-Pure and Simple: How to Make It in Business, Sports and the Arts!|first=Dominic Certo|last=KSJ|date=1 December 2006|via=Google Books}}</ref> Certo is the co-author of the book ''Gold in the Coffins'',<ref name=Fox>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2016/05/10/deported-veteran-gets-new-shot-at-american-dream.html|title=Banished veteran gets new shot at American Dream|first=Hollie|last=McKay|date=10 May 2016|publisher=Fox News}}</ref> released in 2015 and co-written with Len Harac. The novel follows the story of an ex-Marine who builds a gourmet coffee company only to have a Wall Street firm lure them into a predatory [[IPO]]. This led to him being awarded the 2015 Literary Artist Of The Year by the NJ State General Assembly .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bookpleasures.com/websitepublisher/articles/7507/1/Gold-In-The-Coffins-Reviewed-By-Norm-Goldman-of-Bookpleasurescom/Page1.html#.WvmzPaQvzIU|title=Gold In The Coffins Reviewed By Norm Goldman of Bookpleasures.com|website=www.bookpleasures.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Certo, Dominic}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American veterans' rights activists]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:American bodybuilders]]\n[[Category:American business writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American food company founders]]\n[[Category:American strength and conditioning coaches]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American restaurateurs]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American businessperson and author|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Dominic Certo\n| occupation = Businessperson and writer\n| image = Dominic Certo photo.jpg\n| awards = [[American Book Award]] nomination\n| notable_works = ''The Valor of Francesco D'Amini''\n}}\n'''Dominic Certo''' is an American businessperson and author. He has been nominated for the American Book Award, and served as an international judge for the [[International Federation of BodyBuilding & Fitness]] (IFBB).\n\n==Career==\nDominic Certo served in the [[United States Marine Corps]] and is a veteran of the [[Vietnam War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.questia.com/magazine/1G1-452290683/book-review-gold-in-the-coffins|title=\"Book Review: Gold in the Coffins\" |author=Spiro, Keith |date=April 2016 |publisher=The Exceptional Parent}}</ref>  He has since served as an advisor and Chairman of the Advisory Board for [[Operation Homefront]].<ref name=Fox /> In business, Certo has served as President of Hillside Publications,<ref>{{cite book |page=660 |title=Publishers Directory |publisher=Gale Research Company |year=2003}}</ref> and Chairman of The Certo Group, a food services company<ref>{{cite book |page=693 |title=Directory of Chain Restaurant Operators |publisher=Business Guides, Incorporated |year=2008}}</ref> founded by Certo in 1985 and which went public in 2004. He also ran a restaurant chain called LA Caf\u00e9. Certo was knighted by the Royal Family of The Reigning Order of St. John in Russia. He has also received two Presidential Volunteer Service Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=24458787|title=The Certo Group Corp.: Private Company Information - Bloomberg|website=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\n==Bodybuilding==\nIn 1981 Certo was named by the IFBB a judge for that year's [[Mr. Olympia]] competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=KaZeDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT139|title=Muscle Wars|first=Rick|last=Wayne|date=1 January 1985|publisher=BookBaby|via=Google Books|page=139}}</ref> From 1980 to 1986 he served as the Director of the Professional Division Judging for the IFBB, and from 1985 to 1990 he was the Vice President of the Professional Division. He was also the co-producer and director for the 1988 Mr. Olympia and was the awarded the IFBB Silver Medal. Certo is both now a coach and a prior national competitor in the sport himself.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bizstanding.com/p/ifbb-42134058|title=IFBB - Company Profile - BizStanding|website=bizstanding.com}}</ref>\n\n==Writing==\nCerto wrote the book ''The Valor of Francesco D'Amini'', a fictionalized account of a Marine platoon during the Vietnam War.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=_GPXCwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq|title=The Valor of Francesco D'Amini|first=Dominic N.|last=Certo|date=19 April 2016|publisher=Open Road Media|via=Google Books}}</ref> It was nominated for the 1980 [[American Book Award]], and received the 1979 ''Vega'''s Writer Award for Prose.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=QIo6k_tQ0uwC&pg=PA113|title=Success-Pure and Simple: How to Make It in Business, Sports and the Arts!|first=Dominic Certo|last=KSJ|date=1 December 2006|page=113}}</ref> In 2006 Certo self-published the book ''Success-Pure and Simple: How to Make It in Business, Sports and the Arts!'', which focuses on using lessons from athletics and applying them to various professional fields.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books/about/Success_Pure_and_Simple.html?id=QIo6k_tQ0uwC&hl=en&output=html_text&redir_esc=y|title=Success-Pure and Simple: How to Make It in Business, Sports and the Arts!|first=Dominic Certo|last=KSJ|date=1 December 2006|via=Google Books}}</ref> Certo is the co-author of the book ''Gold in the Coffins'',<ref name=Fox>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2016/05/10/deported-veteran-gets-new-shot-at-american-dream.html|title=Banished veteran gets new shot at American Dream|first=Hollie|last=McKay|date=10 May 2016|publisher=Fox News}}</ref> released in 2015 and co-written with Len Harac. The novel follows the story of an ex-Marine who builds a gourmet coffee company only to have a Wall Street firm lure them into a predatory [[IPO]]. This led to him being awarded the 2015 Literary Artist Of The Year by the NJ State General Assembly .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bookpleasures.com/websitepublisher/articles/7